<dl id="n22085d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n22" href="#n22085d">N22 (VI.B.17)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n22all.htm#n22085d"> 85(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Patrizzi</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Generally speaking, however, the Scholastic is to Bruno the pedant, the dabbler in words, as contrasted with the student of nature or of reality. Under this condemnation fell two of the greatest innovators upon the Aristotelian philosophy of his own time,&mdash;Ramus, and Patrizzi. <small> J. Lewis McIntyre, <a name="BRUNO" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BRUNO"><cite title="source">Giordano Bruno</cite></a> (1903) 137-8</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Francesco Patrizzi (1529-1597): Italian philosopher and scientist. </mm> </dd></dl>
